<DOC><DOCNO> AP881014-0258 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2336EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Frank     10-14 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Frank,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Writer-Director-Producer Melvin Frank Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Melvin Frank, a comedywriter-director-producer who helped create ``White Christmas,''``Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House,'' and ``A Touch of Class,''has died of complications from heart surgery. He was 75.   Frank died Thursday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.   Frank teamed with his partner of 38 years, Norman Panama, foreight films, including a string of successful comedies thatincluded ``The Court Jester'' and ``My Favorite Blonde'' and theBroadway musical ``Li'l Abner,'' which they later filmed.   Born in Chicago, Frank met Panama in 1933, and two years laterthey collaborated on comedy material for Milton Berle and Bob Hope.They would go on to earn three Oscar nominations together. Frankgot his fourth nomination for ``A Touch Of Class'' for his writingwith Jack Rose.   Among the films Frank produced were ``Prisoner of SecondAvenue'' and ``Lost and Found.''   He was working on his autobiography when he was hospitalized,said his son, James Frank.   Besides his son, he is survived by his wife, Juliet; daughter,Elizabeth; son, Andrew; and three grandchildren.</TEXT></DOC>